Hands-on lab: Taints & Tolerations
Real scenario · Real commands · kubeadm cluster · ~45 minutes
Real-world scenario: Your company has a 3-node kubeadm cluster. One node has a GPU and should ONLY run ML workloads. Another node is reserved for production apps only. You need to enforce this using Taints and Tolerations — exactly what companies do in production.
1
Understand the concept in 2 minutes
Concept
Think of a Taint as a "NO ENTRY" sign on a node. A Toleration is the special pass that lets a pod enter despite the sign. Without the pass, no pod can land on that node.
A Taint has 3 parts: key=value:effect
The effect controls what happens to pods without a toleration:
— NoSchedule: new pods won't be scheduled here
— NoExecute: existing pods get evicted + new pods blocked
— PreferNoSchedule: K8s tries to avoid this node but not guaranteed
2
Check your cluster nodes first
Practice
Run these — see your nodes
kubectl get nodes
# Note down your worker node names
kubectl get nodes -o wide
# See IPs and roles too
kubectl describe node <worker-node-name> | grep Taint
# See existing taints — master node has one by default!
Expected output (describe on master)
Taints: node-role.kubernetes.io/control-plane:NoSchedule
This is why pods never land on the master node — it has a NoSchedule taint by default! You just discovered a real taint already running in your cluster.
3
Add a taint to your worker node (GPU simulation)
Practice
Pretend your worker node is a GPU node. Taint it so only ML workloads can run there.
Taint the worker node
kubectl taint node <worker-node-name> gpu=true:NoSchedule
# key=gpu, value=true, effect=NoSchedule
kubectl describe node <worker-node-name> | grep Taint
# Confirm the taint was applied
Expected output
Taints: gpu=true:NoSchedule
Now try deploying a normal pod — it should get STUCK
kubectl run normal-pod --image=nginx
kubectl get pods -o wide
# Watch — STATUS will be "Pending" forever!
kubectl describe pod normal-pod | grep -A5 Events
# You'll see: "didn't tolerate" in the events
Expected — pod gets blocked
Warning FailedScheduling 0/2 nodes available: 1 node(s) had untolerated taint {gpu: true}, 1 node(s) had untolerated taint {control-plane}.
Why this matters in interviews
This error message is exactly what you'll see in production when a pod is Pending. Saying "I know this error — it means the pod doesn't have a toleration for the node's taint" immediately shows real experience.
4
Deploy a pod WITH a toleration — it should run
Practice
Now create an ML pod that has the correct toleration. Save this as ml-pod.yaml
ml-pod.yamlCopy
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: ml-pod
  labels:
    app: ml-workload
spec:
  tolerations:             # The special PASS
    - key: "gpu"           # Must match taint key
      operator: "Equal"
      value: "true"        # Must match taint value
      effect: "NoSchedule" # Must match taint effect
  containers:
    - name: ml-container
      image: nginx
      resources:
        requests:
          cpu: "100m"
          memory: "128Mi"
Apply and verify
kubectl apply -f ml-pod.yaml
kubectl get pods -o wide
# ml-pod should be Running on the worker node!
kubectl get pods -o wide --field-selector spec.nodeName=<worker-node-name>
# Confirm it landed on the GPU node specifically
Expected — ml-pod is Running, normal-pod is Pending
NAME STATUS NODE ml-pod Running worker-node-1 normal-pod Pending <none>5
Test NoExecute — evict running pods
5 
Advanced test
NoExecute is stronger than NoSchedule. It kicks out pods that are ALREADY running on the node. This is what happens when a node goes into maintenance.
First remove old taint, add NoExecute
kubectl taint node <worker-node-name> gpu=true:NoSchedule-
# The "-" at the end REMOVES the taint
kubectl run running-pod --image=nginx
kubectl get pods -o wide
# Wait for running-pod to land on worker node
kubectl taint node <worker-node-name> maintenance=true:NoExecute
# Now add NoExecute taint — watch what happens!
kubectl get pods -o wide -w
# -w means watch live. You'll see running-pod get Terminating!
Expected — pod gets evicted live
running-pod Running worker-node-1 running-pod Terminating worker-node-1 ← evicted!
Interview gold — say this
"NoExecute is used in node drain scenarios — when a node needs maintenance, K8s taints it with NoExecute so running pods are safely evicted and rescheduled on other nodes. kubectl drain does this automatically."

6
Clean up + self-check
Cleanup
Remove taints and pods after practice
kubectl taint node <worker-node-name> gpu=true:NoSchedule-
kubectl taint node <worker-node-name> maintenance=true:NoExecute-
kubectl delete pod normal-pod ml-pod running-pod
kubectl describe node <worker-node-name> | grep Taint
# Should show: Taints: <none>
