Question 1 of 5
Imagine you are in an interview right now. Answer this:

You have a 3-node Kubernetes cluster. You want to make sure that ONLY your machine learning pods run on node-1, and no other pods should land there. What do you do?

Take your time — type your answer in your own words. Don't copy from Google. The more you write in your own words, the better feedback I can give you.
Feedback on Question 1
What you got right
Putting a taint gpu=true:NoSchedule on node01 — that is correct. That prevents normal pods from landing on that node.
What you missed — this is the trick in the question
The question said "ONLY ML pods should run there."
A Taint alone does NOT guarantee that. A Toleration only gives a pod permission to land on the tainted node — it does NOT force it there.
So your ML pod with a toleration could still land on node02 or node03 instead!
The complete answer needs TWO things:
Taint on the node     → blocks unwanted pods from coming IN
NodeAffinity on pod   → forces ML pod to go TO that specific node
Together they work like this:
What it doesToolStop other pods from entering node01Taint + NoScheduleForce ML pod to go to node01 specificallyNodeAffinity
The full answer an interviewer wants to hear

"I would taint node01 with gpu=true:NoSchedule so normal pods can't schedule there. Then on the ML pod I'd add a Toleration to allow it past the taint, AND a NodeAffinity rule to force it specifically onto node01. Using only a Taint+Toleration is not enough — the pod could still land on another node."

